article.description:
Eric Snow and Derrick Coleman made a handful of big shots down
the stretch as the streaking 76ers survived a quiet fourth
quarter by Iverson to rally for a 99-93 victory over the Boston
Celtics.
article.headline: Coleman steps to send Sixers to eighth straight win
article.linkText: Sixers hold off old Celtics for their eighth straight win
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Derrick Coleman made his first major contribution of the season, helping the Philadelphia 76ers extend their winning streak to eight games.
Coleman

Iverson

Coleman, who missed the first 10 games of the season after having knee surgery, hit a 3-pointer with 1:10 left and scored a season-high 20 points as the Sixers defeated the Boston Celtics 99-93 Wednesday night. "Having him back is nothing but a plus,'' said Allen Iverson, who had 27 points. "It's more than his basketball skills. The most important thing about having Derrick back is his leadership. He understands what you have to do to win basketball games.'' After Eric Snow made a spinning 12-foot jumper to break a 92-92 tie, Coleman's 3 capped a 9-0 run and gave Philadelphia a 97-92 lead. Iverson made two free throws with 28 seconds left to seal the win. ''(Coleman's) shot was like a dagger,'' Celtics coach Jim O'Brien said. "It was like getting stabbed in the heart.'' Keith Van Horn had 13 points and matched a season-high with 13 rebounds, and Snow added 13 points and eight assists for the 76ers, who are 10-0 at home. The start is Philadelphia's best since winning 22 in a row to begin the 1966-67 season. It's the longest home winning streak since 1999. Paul Pierce had 34 points, Antoine Walker had 19 points, nine rebounds and seven assists and Walter McCarty scored 10 for the Celtics. A driving layup by Walker gave the Celtics a 92-88 lead with 3:36 left. Snow answered with a layup to pull the 76ers within two, and a leaner by Iverson knotted the score at 92. "Eric (Snow) struggled and then hit two big shots down the stretch,'' Sixers coach Larry Brown said. After trailing by as many as 16 in the first half, Philadelphia came back to tie the score at 60 when Iverson made a 3-pointer with 6:40 left in the third. The Sixers scored 13 of the last 16 points of the quarter to lead 75-71 after three. "They were on fire and we couldn't hit a shot,'' Brown said. "But we found a way to win. We hung in there and I'm proud of the effort.'' After a 3-pointer by McCarty, Boston took a 54-38 advantage with 2:45 left in the first half. The 76ers then scored 11 of the last 13 points to pull within seven, 56-49, at the break. "You have to learn to put a team away,'' Boston's Tony Delk said. "We didn't do a good job of that. It was a matter of taking care of the ball.''

Game notes
Monty Williams made his first appearance as a Sixer after missing the first 18 games following surgery on his left knee. he had seven points and two assists in 13 minutes. ... Brown downplayed the Sixers-Celtics rivalry. "I respect those guys but it's hard for me to look at a rivalry when (Larry) Bird's not there, or (Kevin) McHale, Chief (Robert Parish), Dennis Johnson or Danny Ainge,'' Brown said. ... O'Brien pointed to Philadelphia's 20 fast-break points as a problem. "They hurt us on the break,'' O'Brien said. "Any time you give up 20 fast-break points you know it won't be easy.'' ... Williams and Sixers coach Larry Brown were both given technical fouls in the second quarter after Brian Skinner was called for an over-the-back foul.
